","Tong, Shropshire, England":"Tong, Shropshire, England","Tong, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Tong, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1320–Aft 1345":"1320–after 1345","1312–1316":"1312–1316","1320–1336":"1320–1336","1320–1345":"1320–1345","1325–Female":"1325–Deceased","1345–1382":"1345–1382","1295–1328":"1295–1328","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","Aft 1345":"after 1345","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","Aft 1328":"after 1328","1316":"1316","1326":"1326","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1336":"1336","1345":"1345","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","Abt 1320":"about 1320","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","Cheney Longville, Shropshire, England":"Cheney Longville, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Tong, Shropshire, England":"Tong, Shropshire, England","Tong, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Tong, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cheyne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (northeastern Scotland and Shetland): shortened form of   Chaney  , of Norman origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Chaney","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any one of several places in Normandy, Picardy, or Artois (France) named (Le) Quesnay or Quesnoy, or elsewhere in northern France named (Le or La) Chesnay or Chesnoy. The placenames all derive from Old French <i>chesnai</i> or its Normanno-Picard equivalent <i>quesnai</i> ‘oak grove’ (medieval Latin <i>casnetum</i>).","French: variant of <b>Chanet</b>, a habitational name from any of various places called Chanet or Le Chanet, from Latin <i>canna</i> ‘reed’ + the suffix <i>-etum</i> denoting an inhabitant."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":8,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":17,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger de Cheyne II was born in 1320, in Cheney Longville, Shropshire, England, his father, Roger De Cheyne, was 25 and his mother, Mrs. Margery de Cheyne, was 20. He married Isolda De Cheyne II in 1340, in Tong, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. In 1329, at the age of 9, his occupation is listed as collector of taxes in Shropshire, England. He died after 1345, in Cheney Longville, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1320–Aft 1345":"1320–pärast 1345","1312–1316":"1312–1316","1320–1336":"1320–1336","1320–1345":"1320–1345","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1345–1382":"1345–1382","1295–1328":"1295–1328","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","Aft 1345":"pärast 1345","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","Aft 1328":"pärast 1328","1316":"1316","1326":"1326","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1336":"1336","1345":"1345","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","Abt 1320":"umbes 1320","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","Cheney Longville, Shropshire, England":"Cheney Longville, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tong, Shropshire, England":"Tong, Shropshire, England","Tong, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Tong, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1320–Aft 1345":"1320–1345 jälkeen","1312–1316":"1312–1316","1320–1336":"1320–1336","1320–1345":"1320–1345","1325–Female":"1325–Kuollut","1345–1382":"1345–1382","1295–1328":"1295–1328","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","Aft 1345":"1345 jälkeen","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","Aft 1328":"1328 jälkeen","1316":"1316","1326":"1326","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1336":"1336","1345":"1345","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","Abt 1320":"noin 1320","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","Cheney Longville, Shropshire, England":"Cheney Longville, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kunin